<div id="banner">
	<h1>Freedom of Speech, or The DeCSS Haiku</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>Seth Schoen: <a href="http://www.loyalty.org/~schoen/haiku.html">The History of the DeCSS Haiku</a></p>

<p>I wrote the DeCSS Haiku because I was angry at the attempts by lawyers for the entertainment industry and the government to trivialize the free expression rights of programmers and other people engaged in technical communication. I believe, and I said repeatedly in my poem, that one of the reasons courts and others have countenanced the censorship of software is that they do not understand it. </p>

<p>[&#8230;] An observer might be shocked to compare the Bernstein and Corley cases. She would perceive that the courts have concluded that it&#8217;s wrong to censor software in the name of preventing terrorism, but it&#8217;s all right when what&#8217;s at stake is the ability to copy movies.</p>

<p class="posted">posted January 27, 2004 08:42 PM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_politics">Politics</a>) (<a href="001142#comments">2 comments</a>) <a href="001142" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

